Note: ===================================================================
Note: VHDL SEMANTIC ANALYZER
Note: ===================================================================
Note: Semantic analysis for VHDL (VHSIC Hardware Description Language).
Note: Handles entity/architecture validation, type checking, signal analysis,
Note: process validation, and VHDL language compliance verification.

Note: Part of the Translation System
Note: Location: compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/vhdl/vhdl_semantic.runa
Note: ===================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/vhdl/vhdl_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SEMANTIC ANALYZER STRUCTURE
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
VHDL semantic analysis must track many independent design entities at once:
entity/architecture pairs, packages, signals/variables/constants, processes,
sensitivity lists, clock and reset domains. Splitting them into named slots
(rather than one big Dict keyed by kind) lets each analysis pass query its
working set in O(1) and keeps synthesis vs. validation diagnostics in
separate streams so the reporter can apply different severity rules.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
29 x i64 record (232 bytes, offsets 0..224). Slots 0..136 are design-element
registries (List/Dict); 144..168 are synthesis-specific (clock_domains,
reset_signals, sensitivity_lists); 176..208 are diagnostic streams
(validation_errors/warnings, type_errors, synthesis_warnings); 216..224 are
the sticky first-error pair (error_message + has_error) matching the
cmake/dockerfile analyzer convention.
@End Implementation

Type called "VHDLSemanticAnalyzer":
    entities as Integer
    architectures as Integer
    packages as Integer
    package_bodies as Integer
    configurations as Integer
    signals as Integer
    variables as Integer
    constants as Integer
    types as Integer
    subtypes as Integer
    functions as Integer
    procedures as Integer
    processes as Integer
    components as Integer
    port_maps as Integer
    generic_maps as Integer
    libraries as Integer
    use_clauses as Integer
    type_registry as Integer
    signal_drivers as Integer
    sensitivity_lists as Integer
    clock_domains as Integer
    reset_signals as Integer
    validation_errors as Integer
    validation_warnings as Integer
    type_errors as Integer
    synthesis_warnings as Integer
    error_message as Integer
    has_error as Integer
End Type

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ANALYZER CREATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
VHDL analyzers are heavyweight (29 registries spanning declarations,
synthesis state, and four diagnostic streams) so we build them in a single
factory rather than lazily growing slots. This guarantees every downstream
pass sees the same record shape and lets the Type declaration above act as
the canonical layout contract — any new pass just adds another offset
rather than discovering missing slots at runtime.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 232 bytes matching the VHDLSemanticAnalyzer Type (29 i64 slots,
offsets 0..224). Builds Dicts for keyed-by-name registries
(entities/architectures/packages/types/signals/...) and Lists for ordered
streams (processes, libraries, sensitivity_lists, validation_errors, etc.).
Writes are issued in field order so a slot reorder in the Type declaration
must be mirrored here. Slots 216 (error_message) and 224 (has_error)
remain 0 — they are set by set_vhdl_semantic_error only on the first
fatal error, matching the sticky-error convention used by the cmake and
dockerfile analyzers.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_vhdl_semantic_analyzer" returns Integer:
    Note: Create VHDL semantic analyzer for HDL validation

    Let analyzer_size be 232
    Let analyzer be proc allocate from Layout with analyzer_size

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let entities be proc create from Dict
    Let architectures be proc create from Dict
    Let packages be proc create from Dict
    Let package_bodies be proc create from Dict
    Let configurations be proc create from Dict
    Let signals be proc create from Dict
    Let variables be proc create from Dict
    Let constants be proc create from Dict
    Let types be proc create from Dict
    Let subtypes be proc create from Dict
    Let functions be proc create from Dict
    Let procedures be proc create from Dict
    Let processes be proc create from List
    Let components be proc create from Dict
    Let port_maps be proc create from List
    Let generic_maps be proc create from List
    Let libraries be proc create from List
    Let use_clauses be proc create from List
    Let type_registry be proc create from Dict
    Let signal_drivers be proc create from Dict
    Let sensitivity_lists be proc create from List
    Let clock_domains be proc create from List
    Let reset_signals be proc create from List
    Let validation_errors be proc create from List
    Let validation_warnings be proc create from List
    Let type_errors be proc create from List
    Let synthesis_warnings be proc create from List

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0, entities
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8, architectures
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16, packages
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24, package_bodies
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32, configurations
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40, signals
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48, variables
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56, constants
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 64, types
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72, subtypes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80, functions
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88, procedures
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96, processes
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104, components
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 112, port_maps
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 120, generic_maps
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128, libraries
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136, use_clauses
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144, type_registry
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 152, signal_drivers
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 160, sensitivity_lists
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 168, clock_domains
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 176, reset_signals
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 184, validation_errors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 192, validation_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 200, type_errors
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 208, synthesis_warnings
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 216, 0  Note: error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 224, 0  Note: has_error

    Return analyzer
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN ANALYSIS ENTRY POINT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
VHDL design semantics cannot be checked in a single pass — signal drivers
reference architectures that reference entities, and process sensitivity
lists reference signals declared in any visible architecture or package.
The fixed six-phase pipeline below is the minimal dependency ordering:
declarations must exist before design-unit validation, types must be
resolved before signal-driver analysis, and processes can only be
validated after signal usage is known. Reordering phases produces false
"unknown identifier" errors.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two early null guards: analyzer null returns 0 silently (caller bug);
vhdl_ast null records "Null VHDL AST" via set_vhdl_semantic_error and
returns 0. The six phases (collect_vhdl_declarations,
validate_vhdl_design_units, analyze_vhdl_types, analyze_vhdl_signals,
validate_vhdl_processes, validate_vhdl_libraries) each accumulate
diagnostics into the analyzer's streams rather than aborting, so a single
analysis run reports every issue it finds. Final has_error read at offset
224 mirrors the convention used by every other Gungnir frontend analyzer:
1 means a fatal error fired during any phase, return 0 to fail; 0 means
warnings only, return 1.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_vhdl_design" takes analyzer as Integer, vhdl_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform complete semantic analysis on VHDL design

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    If vhdl_ast is equal to 0:
        proc set_vhdl_semantic_error with analyzer, "Null VHDL AST"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Phase 1: Collect design units and declarations
    proc collect_vhdl_declarations with analyzer, vhdl_ast

    Note: Phase 2: Validate entity/architecture relationships
    proc validate_vhdl_design_units with analyzer

    Note: Phase 3: Perform type checking and resolution
    proc analyze_vhdl_types with analyzer

    Note: Phase 4: Validate signal usage and connectivity
    proc analyze_vhdl_signals with analyzer

    Note: Phase 5: Validate processes and concurrent statements
    proc validate_vhdl_processes with analyzer

    Note: Phase 6: Check library usage and dependencies
    proc validate_vhdl_libraries with analyzer

    Let has_error be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 224
    If has_error is equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: DECLARATION COLLECTION
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Reads design_units list from AST. Iterates each, matching its
unit_type string against entity/architecture/package/package_body/
configuration and dispatching to the corresponding collect_vhdl_*
helper. Unknown unit types raise a "Unknown design unit type"
warning via add_vhdl_validation_warning. After the main loop, calls
collect_vhdl_library_clauses to harvest library and use clauses.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_vhdl_declarations" takes analyzer as Integer, vhdl_ast as Integer:
    Note: Collect all VHDL design units and declarations

    @Reasoning:
    First phase collects all entities, architectures, packages, types,
    signals, processes, and other declarations to build comprehensive
    registries for cross-reference validation and type checking.
    @End Reasoning

    Let design_units be proc get_vhdl_design_units with vhdl_ast
    Let unit_count be proc size from List with design_units
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than unit_count:
        Let design_unit be proc get from List with design_units, i
        Let unit_type be proc get_vhdl_design_unit_type with design_unit

        Let is_entity be proc string_equals from StringCore with unit_type, "entity"
        Let is_architecture be proc string_equals from StringCore with unit_type, "architecture"
        Let is_package be proc string_equals from StringCore with unit_type, "package"
        Let is_package_body be proc string_equals from StringCore with unit_type, "package_body"
        Let is_configuration be proc string_equals from StringCore with unit_type, "configuration"

        If is_entity is equal to 1:
            proc collect_vhdl_entity with analyzer, design_unit
        Otherwise If is_architecture is equal to 1:
            proc collect_vhdl_architecture with analyzer, design_unit
        Otherwise If is_package is equal to 1:
            proc collect_vhdl_package with analyzer, design_unit
        Otherwise If is_package_body is equal to 1:
            proc collect_vhdl_package_body with analyzer, design_unit
        Otherwise If is_configuration is equal to 1:
            proc collect_vhdl_configuration with analyzer, design_unit
        Otherwise:
            Let warning be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Unknown design unit type: ", unit_type
            proc add_vhdl_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Collect library and use clauses
    proc collect_vhdl_library_clauses with analyzer, vhdl_ast
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads entity_name from the AST node. Looks up entities_registry
@0. If the name is already present, raises a "Duplicate entity
declaration" error and returns early. Otherwise sets the dictionary
entry and dispatches to collect_entity_ports and
collect_entity_generics for the per-section work.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_vhdl_entity" takes analyzer as Integer, entity_unit as Integer:
    Note: Collect entity declaration

    @Reasoning:
    Register entity with ports, generics, and interface specification
    for architectural binding validation and port mapping checking.
    Entities define the external interface of design components.
    @End Reasoning

    Let entity_name be proc get_vhdl_entity_name with entity_unit
    Let entities_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0

    Note: Check for duplicate entity
    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with entities_registry, entity_name
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Duplicate entity declaration: ", entity_name
        proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    proc set from Dict with entities_registry, entity_name, entity_unit

    Note: Collect entity ports
    proc collect_entity_ports with analyzer, entity_name, entity_unit

    Note: Collect entity generics
    proc collect_entity_generics with analyzer, entity_name, entity_unit
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads architecture_name and entity_name (the entity this architecture
binds to). Forms arch_key = "<entity_name>.<architecture_name>" so
multiple architectures of the same entity coexist with distinct keys.
Looks up architectures_registry @8; on duplicate raises "Duplicate
architecture" error. Otherwise sets the entry and dispatches to
collect_architecture_signals, collect_architecture_components,
collect_architecture_processes.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_vhdl_architecture" takes analyzer as Integer, architecture_unit as Integer:
    Note: Collect architecture declaration

    @Reasoning:
    Register architecture with entity binding, signals, components,
    processes, and concurrent statements for structural and behavioral
    validation. Architectures provide implementation of entities.
    @End Reasoning

    Let architecture_name be proc get_vhdl_architecture_name with architecture_unit
    Let entity_name be proc get_vhdl_architecture_entity with architecture_unit
    Let architectures_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8

    Let arch_key be proc string_concat from StringUtils with entity_name, "."
    Set arch_key to proc string_concat from StringUtils with arch_key, architecture_name

    Note: Check for duplicate architecture
    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with architectures_registry, arch_key
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Duplicate architecture: ", arch_key
        proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    proc set from Dict with architectures_registry, arch_key, architecture_unit

    Note: Collect architecture signals
    proc collect_architecture_signals with analyzer, arch_key, architecture_unit

    Note: Collect architecture components
    proc collect_architecture_components with analyzer, arch_key, architecture_unit

    Note: Collect architecture processes
    proc collect_architecture_processes with analyzer, arch_key, architecture_unit
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads package_name from the AST node. Looks up packages_registry
@16. On duplicate raises "Duplicate package declaration". Otherwise
sets the entry and dispatches to collect_package_types,
collect_package_constants, collect_package_subprograms. These
helpers populate the analyzer's types/constants/functions/procedures
registries with qualified names like "PackageName.TypeName".
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_vhdl_package" takes analyzer as Integer, package_unit as Integer:
    Note: Collect package declaration

    @Reasoning:
    Register package with types, constants, functions, procedures, and
    component declarations for visibility and usage validation. Packages
    provide shared declarations across design units.
    @End Reasoning

    Let package_name be proc get_vhdl_package_name with package_unit
    Let packages_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16

    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with packages_registry, package_name
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Duplicate package declaration: ", package_name
        proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If

    proc set from Dict with packages_registry, package_name, package_unit

    Note: Collect package types
    proc collect_package_types with analyzer, package_name, package_unit

    Note: Collect package constants
    proc collect_package_constants with analyzer, package_name, package_unit

    Note: Collect package functions and procedures
    proc collect_package_subprograms with analyzer, package_name, package_unit
End Process

@Implementation:
Calls get_vhdl_entity_ports. If null returns. Reads signals_registry
@40. Iterates each port: gets port_name, port_direction (in/out/
inout/buffer), port_type. Builds qualified_port_name =
"<entity_name>.<port_name>" via string_concat. Creates a port_info
record via create_vhdl_port_info and sets it under the qualified
name in the signals registry. Calls validate_vhdl_port_direction
to flag illegal direction declarations.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_entity_ports" takes analyzer as Integer, entity_name as Integer, entity_unit as Integer:
    Note: Collect entity port declarations

    @Reasoning:
    Register entity ports with direction (in, out, inout, buffer), type,
    and mode for interface validation and port mapping checking. Ports
    define the entity's external communication interface.
    @End Reasoning

    Let ports_list be proc get_vhdl_entity_ports with entity_unit
    If ports_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let signals_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    Let port_count be proc size from List with ports_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than port_count:
        Let port be proc get from List with ports_list, i
        Let port_name be proc get_vhdl_port_name with port
        Let port_direction be proc get_vhdl_port_direction with port
        Let port_type be proc get_vhdl_port_type with port

        Let qualified_port_name be proc string_concat from StringUtils with entity_name, "."
        Set qualified_port_name to proc string_concat from StringUtils with qualified_port_name, port_name

        Let port_info be proc create_vhdl_port_info with port_direction, port_type
        proc set from Dict with signals_registry, qualified_port_name, port_info

        Note: Validate port direction
        proc validate_vhdl_port_direction with analyzer, entity_name, port_name, port_direction

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Calls get_vhdl_entity_generics. If null returns. Reads
constants_registry @56 (VHDL generics are conceptually compile-time
constants and share registry space with explicit CONSTANT
declarations). Iterates: gets generic_name, generic_type,
generic_default. Builds qualified_generic_name as
"<entity_name>.<generic_name>". Creates generic_info via
create_vhdl_generic_info and sets it in constants_registry.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_entity_generics" takes analyzer as Integer, entity_name as Integer, entity_unit as Integer:
    Note: Collect entity generic declarations

    @Reasoning:
    Register entity generics with types, default values for parameterized
    design validation and generic map checking. Generics provide configurable
    parameters for entities.
    @End Reasoning

    Let generics_list be proc get_vhdl_entity_generics with entity_unit
    If generics_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let constants_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Let generic_count be proc size from List with generics_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than generic_count:
        Let generic be proc get from List with generics_list, i
        Let generic_name be proc get_vhdl_generic_name with generic
        Let generic_type be proc get_vhdl_generic_type with generic
        Let generic_default be proc get_vhdl_generic_default with generic

        Let qualified_generic_name be proc string_concat from StringUtils with entity_name, "."
        Set qualified_generic_name to proc string_concat from StringUtils with qualified_generic_name, generic_name

        Let generic_info be proc create_vhdl_generic_info with generic_type, generic_default
        proc set from Dict with constants_registry, qualified_generic_name, generic_info

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Calls get_vhdl_architecture_signals. If null returns. Reads
signals_registry @40 (shared with entity ports). Iterates each
signal: gets signal_name and signal_type. Builds
qualified_signal_name = "<arch_key>.<signal_name>" so signals from
different architectures of the same entity stay separate. Creates
signal_info via create_vhdl_signal_info and sets it in the registry.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_architecture_signals" takes analyzer as Integer, arch_key as Integer, architecture_unit as Integer:
    Note: Collect architecture signal declarations

    @Reasoning:
    Register architecture signals with types, initial values for
    connectivity analysis and signal usage validation. Signals provide
    communication within architecture implementations.
    @End Reasoning

    Let signals_list be proc get_vhdl_architecture_signals with architecture_unit
    If signals_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let signals_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    Let signal_count be proc size from List with signals_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than signal_count:
        Let signal be proc get from List with signals_list, i
        Let signal_name be proc get_vhdl_signal_name with signal
        Let signal_type be proc get_vhdl_signal_type with signal

        Let qualified_signal_name be proc string_concat from StringUtils with arch_key, "."
        Set qualified_signal_name to proc string_concat from StringUtils with qualified_signal_name, signal_name

        Let signal_info be proc create_vhdl_signal_info with signal_type
        proc set from Dict with signals_registry, qualified_signal_name, signal_info

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Calls get_vhdl_architecture_processes. If null returns. Reads
processes_registry @96 (a List rather than Dict because process
identity is positional, not name-keyed - VHDL allows multiple
unnamed processes in the same architecture). For each process_stmt:
appends to the list, calls analyze_process_sensitivity_list to
populate the analyzer's sensitivity_lists list, and calls
collect_process_variables for the per-process locals.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_architecture_processes" takes analyzer as Integer, arch_key as Integer, architecture_unit as Integer:
    Note: Collect architecture process statements

    @Reasoning:
    Register processes with sensitivity lists and variable declarations
    for behavioral validation and timing analysis. Processes define
    sequential behavior in VHDL architectures.
    @End Reasoning

    Let processes_list be proc get_vhdl_architecture_processes with architecture_unit
    If processes_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let processes_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    Let process_count be proc size from List with processes_list
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than process_count:
        Let process_stmt be proc get from List with processes_list, i
        proc add from List with processes_registry, process_stmt

        Note: Analyze process sensitivity list
        proc analyze_process_sensitivity_list with analyzer, process_stmt

        Note: Collect process variables
        proc collect_process_variables with analyzer, arch_key, process_stmt

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: DESIGN UNIT VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Sequentially calls four validation sub-passes:
  1. validate_entity_architecture_bindings - architectures reference
     existing entities
  2. validate_package_dependencies - use clauses resolve to known
     packages
  3. validate_configuration_specifications - configuration bindings
     pick valid architecture variants
  4. check_design_unit_consistency - top-level cross-checks
Each sub-pass registers any failures via add_vhdl_validation_error.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_vhdl_design_units" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate entity/architecture relationships and design units

    @Reasoning:
    Second phase validates design unit consistency, entity/architecture
    binding, package dependencies, and configuration specifications
    according to VHDL language rules.
    @End Reasoning

    proc validate_entity_architecture_bindings with analyzer
    proc validate_package_dependencies with analyzer
    proc validate_configuration_specifications with analyzer
    proc check_design_unit_consistency with analyzer
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads architectures_registry @8 and entities_registry @0. Lists
the architecture keys (each "entity_name.arch_name"). For each:
gets the architecture_unit, reads its entity_name target via
get_vhdl_architecture_entity, checks entities_registry contains it.
If absent, raises "Architecture references undefined entity"
error. Otherwise calls validate_architecture_port_usage to verify
the architecture uses the entity's ports correctly.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_entity_architecture_bindings" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate entity/architecture bindings

    @Reasoning:
    Validate every architecture has corresponding entity, entity ports
    match architecture usage, and binding specifications are consistent
    according to VHDL entity/architecture relationship rules.
    @End Reasoning

    Let architectures_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let entities_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let arch_keys be proc keys from Dict with architectures_registry
    Let arch_count be proc size from List with arch_keys
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than arch_count:
        Let arch_key be proc get from List with arch_keys, i
        Let architecture_unit be proc get from Dict with architectures_registry, arch_key
        Let entity_name be proc get_vhdl_architecture_entity with architecture_unit

        Note: Check if entity exists
        Let entity_exists be proc contains from Dict with entities_registry, entity_name
        If entity_exists is equal to 0:
            Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Architecture references undefined entity: ", entity_name
            Set error to proc string_concat from StringUtils with error, " in architecture "
            Set error to proc string_concat from StringUtils with error, arch_key
            proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Otherwise:
            Note: Validate port usage consistency
            proc validate_architecture_port_usage with analyzer, arch_key, entity_name
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads entities_registry @0 and looks up entity_unit by name. Calls
get_vhdl_entity_ports - if null returns. Iterates each port:
extracts port_name and port_direction, calls
validate_port_usage_in_architecture which checks that the
architecture neither reads from output-only ports nor writes to
input-only ports.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_architecture_port_usage" takes analyzer as Integer, arch_key as Integer, entity_name as Integer:
    Note: Validate architecture uses entity ports consistently

    @Reasoning:
    Check architecture references entity ports correctly, port directions
    are respected in signal assignments, and all ports are properly
    connected or left open according to VHDL port usage rules.
    @End Reasoning

    Let entities_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let entity_unit be proc get from Dict with entities_registry, entity_name
    Let entity_ports be proc get_vhdl_entity_ports with entity_unit

    If entity_ports is not equal to 0:
        Let port_count be proc size from List with entity_ports
        Let i be 0

        While i is less than port_count:
            Let port be proc get from List with entity_ports, i
            Let port_name be proc get_vhdl_port_name with port
            Let port_direction be proc get_vhdl_port_direction with port

            proc validate_port_usage_in_architecture with analyzer, arch_key, port_name, port_direction

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: TYPE ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Sequentially calls four type sub-passes:
  1. collect_all_types - build type_registry with built-ins +
     user-defined
  2. validate_type_compatibility - signal/variable assignment type
     matching
  3. check_subtype_constraints - subtype range and resolution
     consistency
  4. validate_type_conversions - explicit type conversions are valid
Each sub-pass registers any failures via add_vhdl_type_error.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_vhdl_types" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Perform type checking and resolution

    @Reasoning:
    Third phase performs comprehensive type analysis including type
    compatibility checking, subtype resolution, type conversion validation,
    and aggregate type analysis according to VHDL type system rules.
    @End Reasoning

    proc collect_all_types with analyzer
    proc validate_type_compatibility with analyzer
    proc check_subtype_constraints with analyzer
    proc validate_type_conversions with analyzer
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads type_registry @144. First calls add_vhdl_builtin_types to
seed the registry with the IEEE.std_logic_1164 family (bit, boolean,
integer, std_logic, etc.). Then collect_package_defined_types walks
all packages and registers TYPE declarations; finally
collect_local_type_definitions walks entities and architectures for
their local TYPE declarations.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_all_types" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Collect all type definitions from design units

    @Reasoning:
    Build comprehensive type registry including built-in types, user-defined
    types, subtypes, and array types for type checking and compatibility
    analysis throughout the VHDL design.
    @End Reasoning

    Let type_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144

    Note: Add built-in types
    proc add_vhdl_builtin_types with type_registry

    Note: Collect types from packages
    proc collect_package_defined_types with analyzer

    Note: Collect types from entities and architectures
    proc collect_local_type_definitions with analyzer
End Process

@Implementation:
Builds a List of 14 built-in type names: bit, bit_vector, boolean,
character, integer, natural, positive, string, time, real, std_logic,
std_logic_vector, signed, unsigned. For each name, calls
create_builtin_type_info to make a type_info record (carrying kind
and base type) and sets it in the type_registry under the name. The
std_logic family is included as a built-in even though it is
technically in IEEE.std_logic_1164 - virtually all VHDL designs use
this library so treating it as built-in simplifies type resolution.
@End Implementation
Process called "add_vhdl_builtin_types" takes type_registry as Integer:
    Note: Add VHDL built-in types to registry

    @Reasoning:
    Register standard VHDL types (bit, bit_vector, boolean, integer,
    natural, positive, character, string, time, etc.) for type checking
    and compatibility analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Let builtin_types be proc create from List
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "bit"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "bit_vector"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "boolean"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "character"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "integer"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "natural"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "positive"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "string"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "time"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "real"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "std_logic"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "std_logic_vector"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "signed"
    proc add from List with builtin_types, "unsigned"

    Let type_count be proc size from List with builtin_types
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than type_count:
        Let type_name be proc get from List with builtin_types, i
        Let type_info be proc create_builtin_type_info with type_name
        proc set from Dict with type_registry, type_name, type_info
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Sequentially calls three sub-passes:
  1. validate_signal_assignment_types - checks every signal
     assignment 's <= expr' for type compatibility
  2. validate_variable_assignment_types - same for ':=' in
     processes
  3. validate_subprogram_call_types - actual vs. formal parameter
     type matching at function/procedure calls
Each registers failures via add_vhdl_type_error.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_type_compatibility" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate type compatibility in expressions and assignments

    @Reasoning:
    Check type compatibility in signal assignments, variable assignments,
    function calls, and expressions according to VHDL type matching and
    conversion rules.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Validate signal assignment type compatibility
    proc validate_signal_assignment_types with analyzer

    Note: Validate process variable assignment types
    proc validate_variable_assignment_types with analyzer

    Note: Validate function/procedure call parameter types
    proc validate_subprogram_call_types with analyzer
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SIGNAL ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Sequentially calls four signal sub-passes:
  1. analyze_signal_drivers - populates signal_drivers map
  2. validate_signal_resolution - multi-driver signals need
     resolution functions
  3. check_signal_connectivity - all signals are driven somewhere
  4. detect_signal_usage_issues - unused signals, redundant drives
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_vhdl_signals" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate signal usage and connectivity

    @Reasoning:
    Fourth phase analyzes signal usage patterns, driver analysis, resolution
    functions, and connectivity throughout the VHDL design according to
    signal assignment and resolution rules.
    @End Reasoning

    proc analyze_signal_drivers with analyzer
    proc validate_signal_resolution with analyzer
    proc check_signal_connectivity with analyzer
    proc detect_signal_usage_issues with analyzer
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads signal_drivers Dictionary @152. Calls four collectors in
sequence to populate it: collect_concurrent_signal_drivers (top-
level concurrent assignments), collect_process_signal_drivers
(process bodies), collect_component_output_drivers (component
instantiations). Then calls validate_signal_driver_consistency to
detect multi-driver conflicts.
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_signal_drivers" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Analyze signal driver sources

    @Reasoning:
    Identify all signal drivers from processes, concurrent assignments,
    and component outputs. Check for multiple drivers and resolution
    function requirements according to VHDL signal driving rules.
    @End Reasoning

    Let signal_drivers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 152

    Note: Analyze concurrent signal assignments
    proc collect_concurrent_signal_drivers with analyzer, signal_drivers

    Note: Analyze process signal assignments
    proc collect_process_signal_drivers with analyzer, signal_drivers

    Note: Analyze component output drivers
    proc collect_component_output_drivers with analyzer, signal_drivers

    Note: Check for multiple drivers and resolution requirements
    proc validate_signal_driver_consistency with analyzer, signal_drivers
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads signal_drivers @152. Lists its keys (signal names). For each
signal, gets its drivers list and counts entries. If driver_count
> 1, calls validate_signal_resolution_function which verifies the
signal's declared type carries a resolution function attribute
(e.g. std_logic via the resolved subtype). Single-driver signals
are silently accepted.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_signal_resolution" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate signal resolution functions

    @Reasoning:
    Check signals with multiple drivers have appropriate resolution functions,
    resolution functions are correctly defined, and signal types support
    resolution according to VHDL resolution function rules.
    @End Reasoning

    Let signal_drivers be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 152
    Let driver_keys be proc keys from Dict with signal_drivers
    Let signal_count be proc size from List with driver_keys
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than signal_count:
        Let signal_name be proc get from List with driver_keys, i
        Let drivers_list be proc get from Dict with signal_drivers, signal_name
        Let driver_count be proc size from List with drivers_list

        If driver_count is greater than 1:
            proc validate_signal_resolution_function with analyzer, signal_name
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PROCESS VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Sequentially calls four process sub-passes:
  1. validate_process_sensitivity_lists - sensitivity lists must
     match signals actually read
  2. validate_process_statements - sequential statement validity
  3. check_process_variable_usage - variables read before write
  4. validate_wait_statements - wait on, wait until, wait for syntax
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_vhdl_processes" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate processes and concurrent statements

    @Reasoning:
    Fifth phase validates process sensitivity lists, sequential statements,
    variable usage, wait statements, and process execution semantics
    according to VHDL process and concurrent statement rules.
    @End Reasoning

    proc validate_process_sensitivity_lists with analyzer
    proc validate_process_statements with analyzer
    proc check_process_variable_usage with analyzer
    proc validate_wait_statements with analyzer
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads processes_registry @96 (a List). Iterates each process_stmt
and delegates to validate_individual_process_sensitivity. The
processes_registry is a List because process statements have no
inherent name to key by - architectures may have multiple unnamed
processes.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_process_sensitivity_lists" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate process sensitivity lists

    @Reasoning:
    Check process sensitivity lists include all signals read in the process,
    exclude signals not used, and follow proper sensitivity list construction
    rules for synthesizable and simulation-correct VHDL.
    @End Reasoning

    Let processes_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    Let process_count be proc size from List with processes_registry
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than process_count:
        Let process_stmt be proc get from List with processes_registry, i
        proc validate_individual_process_sensitivity with analyzer, process_stmt
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads the declared sensitivity_list from the process AST node and
the body's statements. Calls
collect_signals_read_in_statements to compute the actual signals
read. If a sensitivity_list exists, calls
compare_sensitivity_with_reads to find mismatches (missing reads,
unnecessary entries). If no sensitivity_list, calls
check_wait_statement_usage - processes without sensitivity lists
must use wait statements to suspend execution.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_individual_process_sensitivity" takes analyzer as Integer, process_stmt as Integer:
    Note: Validate individual process sensitivity list

    @Reasoning:
    Check process sensitivity list matches signals actually read in process
    statements, identify missing or extra signals, and ensure proper
    sensitivity for synthesizable sequential and combinational logic.
    @End Reasoning

    Let sensitivity_list be proc get_vhdl_process_sensitivity_list with process_stmt
    Let process_statements be proc get_vhdl_process_statements with process_stmt

    Note: Collect signals read in process
    Let signals_read be proc collect_signals_read_in_statements with process_statements

    Note: Compare with sensitivity list
    If sensitivity_list is not equal to 0:
        proc compare_sensitivity_with_reads with analyzer, sensitivity_list, signals_read
    Otherwise:
        Note: Process without sensitivity list - check for wait statements
        proc check_wait_statement_usage with analyzer, process_statements
    End If
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads sensitivity_list from process AST. If null returns. Reads
clock_domains @168 and reset_signals @176. Iterates each signal_ref
in the list: extracts signal_name, calls is_vhdl_clock_signal_name
to check for clock-name patterns ("clk", "clock", etc.) and
is_vhdl_reset_signal_name for reset-name patterns. Appends matches
to the corresponding analyzer list. A single signal can match
both (e.g. "clk_rst" in synchronous-reset designs).
@End Implementation
Process called "analyze_process_sensitivity_list" takes analyzer as Integer, process_stmt as Integer:
    Note: Analyze process sensitivity for clock and reset detection

    @Reasoning:
    Identify clock and reset signals from process sensitivity lists for
    timing analysis and sequential logic detection. Proper clock and
    reset identification is crucial for synthesis and timing analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Let sensitivity_list be proc get_vhdl_process_sensitivity_list with process_stmt
    If sensitivity_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let sensitivity_count be proc size from List with sensitivity_list
    Let clock_domains be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 168
    Let reset_signals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 176
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than sensitivity_count:
        Let signal_ref be proc get from List with sensitivity_list, i
        Let signal_name be proc get_vhdl_sensitivity_signal_name with signal_ref

        Note: Check for clock signal patterns
        Let is_clock_like be proc is_vhdl_clock_signal_name with signal_name
        If is_clock_like is equal to 1:
            proc add from List with clock_domains, signal_name
        End If

        Note: Check for reset signal patterns
        Let is_reset_like be proc is_vhdl_reset_signal_name with signal_name
        If is_reset_like is equal to 1:
            proc add from List with reset_signals, signal_name
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: LIBRARY VALIDATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Sequentially calls four library sub-passes:
  1. validate_library_clauses - each LIBRARY clause references a
     real library
  2. validate_use_clauses - each USE clause resolves to a known
     package
  3. check_package_visibility - referenced items are actually
     exposed by the imported package
  4. validate_standard_library_usage - standard libraries (ieee,
     std) used correctly
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_vhdl_libraries" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Check library usage and dependencies

    @Reasoning:
    Sixth phase validates library clauses, use clauses, package dependencies,
    and visibility rules according to VHDL library and visibility
    specifications.
    @End Reasoning

    proc validate_library_clauses with analyzer
    proc validate_use_clauses with analyzer
    proc check_package_visibility with analyzer
    proc validate_standard_library_usage with analyzer
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads libraries List @128. Iterates each library_clause: gets the
library_name via get_vhdl_library_name. Calls
validate_vhdl_library_name (general name-validity check) and
check_standard_library_reference (flags the well-known std/ieee/
work libraries for special-case handling).
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_library_clauses" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate library clause declarations

    @Reasoning:
    Check library clauses reference valid libraries, libraries are available
    in the design environment, and library usage follows VHDL library
    specification rules.
    @End Reasoning

    Let libraries be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128
    Let library_count be proc size from List with libraries
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than library_count:
        Let library_clause be proc get from List with libraries, i
        Let library_name be proc get_vhdl_library_name with library_clause

        Note: Validate library name
        proc validate_vhdl_library_name with analyzer, library_name

        Note: Check if standard library
        proc check_standard_library_reference with analyzer, library_name

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Implementation:
Reads use_clauses List @136. Iterates each use_clause and
delegates to validate_individual_use_clause which checks that the
referenced library is declared, the package exists in that library,
and the selected items (.all or specific names) resolve correctly.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_use_clauses" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Note: Validate use clause specifications

    @Reasoning:
    Check use clauses reference valid packages, package items exist,
    and visibility rules are followed according to VHDL use clause
    and package visibility specifications.
    @End Reasoning

    Let use_clauses be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
    Let use_count be proc size from List with use_clauses
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than use_count:
        Let use_clause be proc get from List with use_clauses, i
        proc validate_individual_use_clause with analyzer, use_clause
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: UTILITY FUNCTIONS
Note: ===================================================================

@Implementation:
Builds a List of clock-name patterns: "clk", "clock", "CLK",
"CLOCK". Loops calling string_contains for each pattern against
signal_name. Returns 1 on the first match. Returns 0 if no pattern
matches. Note this is a SUBSTRING check (so "sys_clk" also matches
"clk"), giving liberal detection of clock signals; downstream
synthesis can still treat the heuristic match as advisory and
require an explicit attribute for the authoritative answer.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_vhdl_clock_signal_name" takes signal_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if signal name indicates a clock signal

    @Reasoning:
    Clock signals typically follow VHDL naming conventions like clk, clock,
    CLK, etc. Use pattern matching to identify likely clock signals for
    timing analysis and sequential logic detection.
    @End Reasoning

    Let clock_patterns be proc create from List
    proc add from List with clock_patterns, "clk"
    proc add from List with clock_patterns, "clock"
    proc add from List with clock_patterns, "CLK"
    proc add from List with clock_patterns, "CLOCK"

    Let pattern_count be proc size from List with clock_patterns
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than pattern_count:
        Let pattern be proc get from List with clock_patterns, i
        Let contains_pattern be proc string_contains from StringUtils with signal_name, pattern
        If contains_pattern is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Implementation:
Builds a List of reset-name patterns: "rst", "reset", "RST",
"RESET", "resetn", "rst_n". Loops calling string_contains for each
pattern against signal_name; returns 1 on first match, 0 otherwise.
The _n variants ("rst_n", "resetn") signal active-low resets - this
predicate doesn't distinguish polarity (treats both as reset), and
the downstream synthesiser handles the polarity inference.
@End Implementation
Process called "is_vhdl_reset_signal_name" takes signal_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if signal name indicates a reset signal

    @Reasoning:
    Reset signals typically follow VHDL naming conventions like rst, reset,
    RST, etc. Use pattern matching to identify likely reset signals for
    reset synchronization analysis.
    @End Reasoning

    Let reset_patterns be proc create from List
    proc add from List with reset_patterns, "rst"
    proc add from List with reset_patterns, "reset"
    proc add from List with reset_patterns, "RST"
    proc add from List with reset_patterns, "RESET"
    proc add from List with reset_patterns, "resetn"
    proc add from List with reset_patterns, "rst_n"

    Let pattern_count be proc size from List with reset_patterns
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than pattern_count:
        Let pattern be proc get from List with reset_patterns, i
        Let contains_pattern be proc string_contains from StringUtils with signal_name, pattern
        If contains_pattern is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Implementation:
Builds a List of the four valid directions: "in", "out", "inout",
"buffer". Linear-searches via string_equals; sets is_valid = 1 on
match. If no match, builds an error string
"Invalid port direction in entity <ent>, port <port>: <direction>"
via three string_concat calls and appends via
add_vhdl_validation_error.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_vhdl_port_direction" takes analyzer as Integer, entity_name as Integer, port_name as Integer, port_direction as Integer:
    Note: Validate VHDL port direction specification

    @Reasoning:
    VHDL port directions must be valid keywords (in, out, inout, buffer)
    and follow VHDL port declaration rules. Invalid directions cause
    compilation errors and interface mismatches.
    @End Reasoning

    Let valid_directions be proc create from List
    proc add from List with valid_directions, "in"
    proc add from List with valid_directions, "out"
    proc add from List with valid_directions, "inout"
    proc add from List with valid_directions, "buffer"

    Let direction_count be proc size from List with valid_directions
    Let is_valid be 0
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than direction_count:
        Let valid_direction be proc get from List with valid_directions, i
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with port_direction, valid_direction
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Set is_valid to 1
            Break
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If is_valid is equal to 0:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Invalid port direction in entity ", entity_name
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringUtils with error, ", port "
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringUtils with error, port_name
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringUtils with error, ": "
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringUtils with error, port_direction
        proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
VHDL library names are syntactically just identifiers but participate in
the use_clauses lookup, so a malformed library name silently breaks every
`use lib.pkg.all` clause that references it. Validating at declaration
time produces a single targeted error instead of a cascade of unresolved-
reference diagnostics downstream.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Two independent checks, both routed through add_vhdl_validation_error so
analyze_vhdl_design's has_error read picks them up. (1) First-character
ASCII range 48..57 detects a leading digit, which VHDL identifier rules
forbid. (2) is_vhdl_reserved_word does an exact match against the ~97
reserved-word table; the input is expected to be lower-cased by the
parser since VHDL is case-insensitive on identifiers. The error string
is reused via Set on the second branch — this is safe because both
branches build independent concat chains, but it does mean a malformed
name that is also reserved emits both errors (intentional: both rule
violations matter).
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_vhdl_library_name" takes analyzer as Integer, library_name as Integer:
    Note: Validate VHDL library name

    Note: Check for valid identifier format
    Let first_char be proc string_char_at from StringCore with library_name, 0
    If first_char is greater than or equal to 48 and first_char is less than or equal to 57:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Library name cannot start with digit: ", library_name
        proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If

    Note: Check for VHDL reserved words
    Let is_reserved be proc is_vhdl_reserved_word with library_name
    If is_reserved is equal to 1:
        Set error to proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Library name is reserved word: ", library_name
        proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
VHDL-93/2008 reserves ~97 keywords that cannot be used as identifiers
(library names, signal names, generic labels). This predicate is the single
source of truth for reserved-word checks across the analyzer and is invoked
during library/signal/component validation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds the full reserved-word list once (abs..xor, lower-case canonical
spelling), then linear-scans for an exact match via string_equals. VHDL is
case-insensitive on identifiers but callers are expected to have already
lower-cased the input. Returns 1 on match, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
The list is rebuilt every call; for hot paths this can be hoisted to a
module-scope cached List. Linear scan of ~97 entries is acceptable for the
current call frequency (per-identifier in declaration validation).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "is_vhdl_reserved_word" takes word as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if word is a VHDL reserved keyword

    Let reserved_words be proc create from List
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "abs"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "access"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "after"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "alias"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "all"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "and"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "architecture"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "array"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "assert"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "attribute"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "begin"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "block"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "body"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "buffer"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "bus"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "case"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "component"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "configuration"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "constant"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "disconnect"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "downto"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "else"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "elsif"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "end"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "entity"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "exit"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "file"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "for"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "function"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "generate"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "generic"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "group"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "guarded"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "if"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "impure"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "in"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "inertial"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "inout"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "is"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "label"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "library"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "linkage"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "literal"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "loop"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "map"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "mod"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "nand"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "new"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "next"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "nor"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "not"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "null"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "of"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "on"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "open"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "or"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "others"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "out"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "package"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "port"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "postponed"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "procedure"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "process"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "pure"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "range"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "record"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "register"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "reject"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "rem"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "report"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "return"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "rol"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "ror"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "select"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "severity"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "signal"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "shared"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "sla"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "sll"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "sra"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "srl"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "subtype"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "then"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "to"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "transport"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "type"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "unaffected"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "units"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "until"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "use"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "variable"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "wait"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "when"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "while"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "with"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "xnor"
    proc add from List with reserved_words, "xor"

    Let word_count be proc size from List with reserved_words
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than word_count:
        Let reserved_word be proc get from List with reserved_words, i
        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with word, reserved_word
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: ERROR HANDLING
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Records the first fatal failure that should abort further analysis (null
AST, malformed top-level unit). Distinct from add_vhdl_validation_error
which collects recoverable issues; this one flips the sticky has_error flag.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Writes the error_message string handle into offset 216 and sets has_error=1
at offset 224. Single-shot — does not clear an existing entry.
@End Implementation

Process called "set_vhdl_semantic_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Set semantic analysis error

    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 216, error_message
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 224, 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recoverable validation issues are accumulated rather than fail-fast: the
user should see every problem from one analysis pass, not just the first.
Distinct from set_vhdl_semantic_error which is reserved for fatal AST
shape failures.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loads the validation_errors list from offset 184 and appends the string
handle. Caller retains ownership of the string; analyzer's destructor frees
the list and its contents in bulk.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_vhdl_validation_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation error to error list

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 184
    proc add from List with errors, error_message
End Process

@Reasoning:
Non-fatal style/synthesizability concerns flow to a separate stream from
hard errors so the reporter can show them with lower severity and the
build can be allowed to proceed when only warnings are present.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Appends to the validation_warnings list at offset 192. Same ownership model
as add_vhdl_validation_error.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_vhdl_validation_warning" takes analyzer as Integer, warning_message as Integer:
    Note: Add validation warning to warning list

    Let warnings be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 192
    proc add from List with warnings, warning_message
End Process

@Reasoning:
Type-system violations (signal-type mismatches, illegal subtype narrowing,
mismatched array bounds) are kept in their own stream because type-checking
diagnostics are often more actionable for the user than generic validation
errors and may need a different display format.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Appends to the type_errors list at offset 200. vhdl_semantic_has_errors
sums this count with validation_errors when reporting overall failure.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_vhdl_type_error" takes analyzer as Integer, error_message as Integer:
    Note: Add type error to error list

    Let type_errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 200
    proc add from List with type_errors, error_message
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PUBLIC API
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public one-shot driver: callers that don't want to manage the analyzer
lifecycle get an analyzer handle back containing all diagnostic streams.
Returning the analyzer rather than the boolean result lets callers query
errors/warnings/type_errors lists post-analysis.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a fresh analyzer via create_vhdl_semantic_analyzer, returns 0 on
allocation failure, otherwise runs analyze_vhdl_design and returns the
populated analyzer regardless of analysis success — diagnostics are queried
via the dedicated getters.
@End Implementation

Process called "vhdl_semantic_analyze" takes vhdl_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Perform semantic analysis on VHDL AST

    Let analyzer be proc create_vhdl_semantic_analyzer
    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let result be proc analyze_vhdl_design with analyzer, vhdl_ast
    Return analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Read-only accessor letting reporters and tests iterate the validation
errors list without poking analyzer internals at offset 184.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-analyzer guard returns 0 (callers must treat that as "no list"); on
success reads the validation_errors list handle at offset 184.
@End Implementation

Process called "vhdl_semantic_get_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get validation errors from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 184
End Process

@Reasoning:
Accessor for the lower-severity warning stream, kept separate from errors
so the reporter can apply distinct formatting and the build can choose
to ignore warnings while still treating errors as fatal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-analyzer guard returns 0; on success returns the validation_warnings
list handle at offset 192.
@End Implementation

Process called "vhdl_semantic_get_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get validation warnings from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 192
End Process

@Reasoning:
Exposes the dedicated type-error stream so type-aware tooling (e.g. an IDE
type panel) can render type diagnostics distinctly from generic errors.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-analyzer guard returns 0; on success returns the type_errors list
handle at offset 200.
@End Implementation

Process called "vhdl_semantic_get_type_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get type errors from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 200
End Process

@Reasoning:
Synthesis warnings are a VHDL-specific concern (latch inferences, missing
sensitivity entries, non-synthesizable constructs) and live in their own
stream so synthesis tooling can surface them without mixing in generic
validation noise.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-analyzer guard returns 0; on success returns the synthesis_warnings
list handle at offset 208.
@End Implementation

Process called "vhdl_semantic_get_synthesis_warnings" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get synthesis warnings from semantic analysis

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 208
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single boolean check the driver uses to decide whether to proceed with
later compilation phases. Type errors and validation errors are both
treated as fatal here; warnings are not — they live in their own streams.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null analyzer is treated as "errored" (returns 1) to fail safe. Otherwise
sums the sizes of the validation_errors list (offset 184) and type_errors
list (offset 200). Returns a count rather than 0/1 — callers in this
analyzer's public API check "is greater than 0".
@End Implementation

Process called "vhdl_semantic_has_errors" takes analyzer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if semantic analysis found any errors

    If analyzer is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 184
    Let error_count be proc size from List with errors

    Let type_errors be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 200
    Let type_error_count be proc size from List with type_errors

    Return error_count plus type_error_count
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: AST ACCESSORS
Note: ===================================================================
Note: These read the parser's dictionary-backed AST nodes. Each node is a
Note: Dictionary whose integer "type" attribute is one of Parser.NODE_*; the
Note: remaining attributes ("name", "ports", "generics", "statements", ...)
Note: mirror the keys set by vhdl_parser. The accessors give the analyzer a
Note: single, parser-shape-aware reading layer so a parser attribute rename
Note: only touches this region.

@Reasoning:
The root design-file node stores its child design units under the
"design_units" attribute as an ordered List. Returning that list directly
lets the collector iterate units in source order.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Dict.get(node, "design_units"); 0 propagates as an empty/absent list.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_vhdl_design_units" takes vhdl_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    If vhdl_ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from Dict with vhdl_ast, "design_units"
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser tags every node with an integer kind under "type". The collector
dispatches on a lowercase string, so this accessor maps the design-unit
kind constants to their canonical VHDL keyword. Non-design-unit kinds map
to "unknown" so the collector's Otherwise branch reports them.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the integer "type"; compare against Parser.NODE_ENTITY/ARCHITECTURE/
PACKAGE/PACKAGE_BODY/CONFIGURATION; return the matching keyword string.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_vhdl_design_unit_type" takes design_unit as Integer returns Integer:
    If design_unit is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "unknown"
    End If
    Let kind be proc get from Dict with design_unit, "type"
    If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_ENTITY:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "entity"
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_ARCHITECTURE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "architecture"
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_PACKAGE:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "package"
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_PACKAGE_BODY:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "package_body"
    End If
    If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_CONFIGURATION:
        Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "configuration"
    End If
    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "unknown"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Entity/architecture/package nodes store their declared identifier under
"name"; architecture additionally stores the bound entity under
"entity_name".
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Dict.get with the corresponding attribute key.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_vhdl_entity_name" takes entity_unit as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with entity_unit, "name"
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_entity_ports" takes entity_unit as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with entity_unit, "ports"
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_entity_generics" takes entity_unit as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with entity_unit, "generics"
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_architecture_name" takes architecture_unit as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with architecture_unit, "name"
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_architecture_entity" takes architecture_unit as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with architecture_unit, "entity_name"
End Process

@Reasoning:
An architecture's signals and processes are not stored under dedicated
attributes; they live in the "declarations" and "statements" lists
respectively, intermixed with other node kinds. These accessors filter
those lists by node kind so callers receive only the nodes they expect.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read "declarations"; build a fresh List of the entries whose "type" equals
Parser.NODE_SIGNAL_DECL. Processes: read "statements"; collect entries
whose "type" equals Parser.NODE_PROCESS.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_vhdl_architecture_signals" takes architecture_unit as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc create from List
    Let declarations be proc get from Dict with architecture_unit, "declarations"
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc get from List with declarations, i
        Let kind be proc get from Dict with decl, "type"
        If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_SIGNAL_DECL:
            proc add from List with result, decl
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_architecture_processes" takes architecture_unit as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be proc create from List
    Let statements be proc get from Dict with architecture_unit, "statements"
    If statements is equal to 0:
        Return result
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with statements
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let stmt be proc get from List with statements, i
        Let kind be proc get from Dict with stmt, "type"
        If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_PROCESS:
            proc add from List with result, stmt
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
A port/generic interface element is a NODE_PORT_DECL/NODE_GENERIC_DECL node
carrying a "names" list (one declaration may name several formals), a
"mode" string (in/out/inout/buffer/linkage) and a "type" subtype
indication node, plus an optional "default_value". The analyzer treats one
port as one name, so the name accessor returns the first entry of "names".
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
get_vhdl_port_name returns names[0] (or 0 if absent). Direction reads
"mode"; type reads "type". Generic accessors mirror this with the default
read from "default_value".
@End Implementation
Process called "get_vhdl_port_name" takes port as Integer returns Integer:
    Let names be proc get from Dict with port, "names"
    If names is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with names
    If count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with names, 0
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_port_direction" takes port as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with port, "mode"
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_port_type" takes port as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with port, "subtype"
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_generic_name" takes generic as Integer returns Integer:
    Let names be proc get from Dict with generic, "names"
    If names is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with names
    If count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with names, 0
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_generic_type" takes generic as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with generic, "subtype"
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_generic_default" takes generic as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with generic, "default_value"
End Process

@Reasoning:
A signal declaration stores its identifiers under "names" and its subtype
indication under "type" (the parser overwrites the node-kind tag with the
subtype node for signal declarations). One signal-info per name is built by
the collector, so the name accessor returns the first name.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
get_vhdl_signal_name returns names[0]; get_vhdl_signal_type returns "type".
@End Implementation
Process called "get_vhdl_signal_name" takes signal as Integer returns Integer:
    Let names be proc get from Dict with signal, "names"
    If names is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with names
    If count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with names, 0
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_signal_type" takes signal as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with signal, "subtype"
End Process

@Reasoning:
A process node stores its sensitivity list under "sensitivity_list" (a List
of expression nodes naming signals) and its body under "statements".
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Direct Dict.get of the two attributes.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_vhdl_process_sensitivity_list" takes process_stmt as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with process_stmt, "sensitivity_list"
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_process_statements" takes process_stmt as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with process_stmt, "statements"
End Process

@Reasoning:
A sensitivity-list entry is an identifier expression node whose referenced
signal name is stored under "name".
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Dict.get(signal_ref, "name").
@End Implementation
Process called "get_vhdl_sensitivity_signal_name" takes signal_ref as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with signal_ref, "name"
End Process

@Reasoning:
A library clause stores the declared library names under "libraries".
The accessor returns the first name, the common single-library case the
validator reports against.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read "libraries"; return entry 0 or 0 when absent.
@End Implementation
Process called "get_vhdl_library_name" takes library_clause as Integer returns Integer:
    Let libs be proc get from Dict with library_clause, "libraries"
    If libs is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with libs
    If count is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get from List with libs, 0
End Process

Process called "get_vhdl_package_name" takes package_unit as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc get from Dict with package_unit, "name"
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: INFO RECORD CONSTRUCTORS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
A port-info record packages a port's direction and type behind a small
Dictionary so the signals registry can answer both "what direction" and
"what type" with one stored value. Using a Dictionary keeps the record
self-describing and avoids a fixed-offset struct that would have to be kept
in sync separately.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Create a Dict; store "kind"="port", "direction", "type". Returns the dict.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_vhdl_port_info" takes port_direction as Integer, port_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let info be proc create from Dict
    proc set from Dict with info, "kind", "port"
    proc set from Dict with info, "direction", port_direction
    proc set from Dict with info, "type", port_type
    Return info
End Process

Process called "create_vhdl_generic_info" takes generic_type as Integer, generic_default as Integer returns Integer:
    Let info be proc create from Dict
    proc set from Dict with info, "kind", "generic"
    proc set from Dict with info, "type", generic_type
    proc set from Dict with info, "default", generic_default
    Return info
End Process

Process called "create_vhdl_signal_info" takes signal_type as Integer returns Integer:
    Let info be proc create from Dict
    proc set from Dict with info, "kind", "signal"
    proc set from Dict with info, "type", signal_type
    Return info
End Process

@Reasoning:
Built-in scalar/array types (std_logic, integer, boolean, ...) get a
synthetic info record so type checks against them succeed without a user
declaration. The record marks itself builtin so diagnostics can phrase
messages differently from user types.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Create a Dict; store "kind"="builtin_type", "name"=type_name. Returns it.
@End Implementation
Process called "create_builtin_type_info" takes type_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let info be proc create from Dict
    proc set from Dict with info, "kind", "builtin_type"
    proc set from Dict with info, "name", type_name
    Return info
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: COLLECTORS (Phase 1 helpers)
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
A package body re-implements the subprograms a package declares; for
cross-reference purposes the analyzer records its name in the
package_bodies registry @24 so a body without a matching package
declaration can be reported during dependency checking.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read package-body name; register in package_bodies registry @24 keyed by
name. Duplicate bodies raise a validation error.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_vhdl_package_body" takes analyzer as Integer, design_unit as Integer:
    Let name be proc get_vhdl_package_name with design_unit
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with registry, name
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Duplicate package body: ", name
        proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If
    proc set from Dict with registry, name, design_unit
    proc collect_package_types with analyzer, name, design_unit
    proc collect_package_constants with analyzer, name, design_unit
    proc collect_package_subprograms with analyzer, name, design_unit
End Process

@Reasoning:
A configuration binds component instances to specific entity/architecture
pairs. It is registered in the configurations registry @32 by name for use
in binding validation.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read configuration name (stored under "name"); register in @32; duplicate
configurations raise an error.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_vhdl_configuration" takes analyzer as Integer, design_unit as Integer:
    Let name be proc get from Dict with design_unit, "name"
    If name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    Let exists be proc contains from Dict with registry, name
    If exists is equal to 1:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Duplicate configuration: ", name
        proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
        Return
    End If
    proc set from Dict with registry, name, design_unit
End Process

@Reasoning:
Library clauses make external libraries (ieee, work, std, ...) visible.
The parser keeps them in the root node's "context" list as
NODE_LIBRARY_CLAUSE / NODE_USE_CLAUSE nodes. This collector files library
clauses into the libraries list @128 and use clauses into use_clauses
@136 for later visibility and dependency validation.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read root "context" list; for each entry switch on "type": library clauses
append their first library name to @128; use clauses append the whole node
to @136.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_vhdl_library_clauses" takes analyzer as Integer, vhdl_ast as Integer:
    Let design_units be proc get_vhdl_design_units with vhdl_ast
    If design_units is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let libraries be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128
    Let use_clauses be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
    Let unit_count be proc size from List with design_units
    Let u be 0
    While u is less than unit_count:
        Let unit be proc get from List with design_units, u
        Let context be proc get from Dict with unit, "context"
        If context is not equal to 0:
            Let count be proc size from List with context
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let item be proc get from List with context, i
                Let kind be proc get from Dict with item, "type"
                If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_LIBRARY_CLAUSE:
                    Let lib_name be proc get_vhdl_library_name with item
                    If lib_name is not equal to 0:
                        proc add from List with libraries, lib_name
                    End If
                Otherwise If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_USE_CLAUSE:
                    proc add from List with use_clauses, item
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set u to u plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Local (architecture/process) type definitions extend the type registry so
references to user types resolve. This walks every collected architecture's
declarations for NODE_TYPE_DECL nodes and registers them.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate the architectures registry @8 values; for each architecture read
its "declarations" and register every NODE_TYPE_DECL's "name" in the type
registry @144 with a builtin-style info record so later lookups succeed.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_local_type_definitions" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let architectures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let type_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144
    Let arch_keys be proc keys from Dict with architectures
    Let key_count be proc size from List with arch_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let arch_key be proc get from List with arch_keys, k
        Let architecture be proc get from Dict with architectures, arch_key
        Let declarations be proc get from Dict with architecture, "declarations"
        If declarations is not equal to 0:
            Let decl_count be proc size from List with declarations
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than decl_count:
                Let decl be proc get from List with declarations, i
                Let decl_kind be proc get from Dict with decl, "type"
                If decl_kind is equal to Parser.NODE_TYPE_DECL:
                    Let type_name be proc get from Dict with decl, "name"
                    If type_name is not equal to 0:
                        Let info be proc create_builtin_type_info with type_name
                        proc set from Dict with type_registry, type_name, info
                    End If
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
The package collectors register a package's exported declarations
(types, constants, subprograms) in the shared registries so use-clauses
that import them resolve. All three share the same walk shape over the
package's "declarations" list, filtering by the relevant node kind.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
collect_package_types registers NODE_TYPE_DECL/NODE_SUBTYPE_DECL names into
the type registry @144 keyed by "<package_name>.<type_name>".
collect_package_constants registers NODE_CONSTANT_DECL first names into the
constants registry @56. collect_package_subprograms registers
NODE_FUNCTION_DECL/NODE_PROCEDURE_DECL names into functions @80 /
procedures @88.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_package_types" takes analyzer as Integer, package_name as Integer, package_unit as Integer:
    Let declarations be proc get from Dict with package_unit, "declarations"
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let type_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144
    Let count be proc size from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc get from List with declarations, i
        Let kind be proc get from Dict with decl, "type"
        If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_TYPE_DECL:
            Let type_name be proc get from Dict with decl, "name"
            If type_name is not equal to 0:
                Let qualified be proc string_concat from StringUtils with package_name, "."
                Set qualified to proc string_concat from StringUtils with qualified, type_name
                Let info be proc create_builtin_type_info with type_name
                proc set from Dict with type_registry, qualified, info
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Process called "collect_package_constants" takes analyzer as Integer, package_name as Integer, package_unit as Integer:
    Let declarations be proc get from Dict with package_unit, "declarations"
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let constants_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 56
    Let count be proc size from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc get from List with declarations, i
        Let kind be proc get from Dict with decl, "type"
        If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_CONSTANT_DECL:
            Let names be proc get from Dict with decl, "names"
            If names is not equal to 0:
                Let name_count be proc size from List with names
                If name_count is greater than 0:
                    Let const_name be proc get from List with names, 0
                    Let qualified be proc string_concat from StringUtils with package_name, "."
                    Set qualified to proc string_concat from StringUtils with qualified, const_name
                    proc set from Dict with constants_registry, qualified, decl
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Process called "collect_package_subprograms" takes analyzer as Integer, package_name as Integer, package_unit as Integer:
    Let declarations be proc get from Dict with package_unit, "declarations"
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let functions_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    Let procedures_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
    Let count be proc size from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc get from List with declarations, i
        Let kind be proc get from Dict with decl, "type"
        Let sub_name be proc get from Dict with decl, "name"
        If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_FUNCTION_DECL:
            If sub_name is not equal to 0:
                Let qualified be proc string_concat from StringUtils with package_name, "."
                Set qualified to proc string_concat from StringUtils with qualified, sub_name
                proc set from Dict with functions_registry, qualified, decl
            End If
        Otherwise If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_PROCEDURE_DECL:
            If sub_name is not equal to 0:
                Let qualified be proc string_concat from StringUtils with package_name, "."
                Set qualified to proc string_concat from StringUtils with qualified, sub_name
                proc set from Dict with procedures_registry, qualified, decl
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Process called "collect_package_defined_types" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let packages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let pkg_keys be proc keys from Dict with packages
    Let key_count be proc size from List with pkg_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let pkg_name be proc get from List with pkg_keys, k
        Let package_unit be proc get from Dict with packages, pkg_name
        proc collect_package_types with analyzer, pkg_name, package_unit
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A component declaration inside an architecture names an entity-like
template that is later instantiated. Collecting them lets instantiation
checks confirm a component is declared before use. They live in the
architecture's "declarations" list as NODE_COMPONENT_DECL nodes.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the architecture's "declarations"; register every NODE_COMPONENT_DECL
"name" into the components registry @104 keyed by "<arch_key>.<name>".
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_architecture_components" takes analyzer as Integer, arch_key as Integer, architecture_unit as Integer:
    Let declarations be proc get from Dict with architecture_unit, "declarations"
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let components_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 104
    Let count be proc size from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc get from List with declarations, i
        Let kind be proc get from Dict with decl, "type"
        If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_COMPONENT_DECL:
            Let comp_name be proc get from Dict with decl, "name"
            If comp_name is not equal to 0:
                Let qualified be proc string_concat from StringUtils with arch_key, "."
                Set qualified to proc string_concat from StringUtils with qualified, comp_name
                proc set from Dict with components_registry, qualified, decl
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Process-local variables (NODE_VARIABLE_DECL inside the process's
"declarations") are recorded so variable-vs-signal assignment checks and
use-before-definition checks can run. Variables are registry @48 keyed by
"<arch_key>.<process_index_or_name>.<var_name>"; here we use the process
node pointer's first variable name qualified by arch_key for uniqueness.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read process "declarations"; for each NODE_VARIABLE_DECL, register each
name into the variables registry @48 keyed by "<arch_key>.<var_name>".
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_process_variables" takes analyzer as Integer, arch_key as Integer, process_stmt as Integer:
    Let declarations be proc get from Dict with process_stmt, "declarations"
    If declarations is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let variables_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let count be proc size from List with declarations
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let decl be proc get from List with declarations, i
        Let kind be proc get from Dict with decl, "type"
        If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_VARIABLE_DECL:
            Let names be proc get from Dict with decl, "names"
            If names is not equal to 0:
                Let name_count be proc size from List with names
                Let j be 0
                While j is less than name_count:
                    Let var_name be proc get from List with names, j
                    Let qualified be proc string_concat from StringUtils with arch_key, "."
                    Set qualified to proc string_concat from StringUtils with qualified, var_name
                    proc set from Dict with variables_registry, qualified, decl
                    Set j to j plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SIGNAL DRIVER COLLECTION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Multi-driver detection requires knowing every concurrent assignment target
across all architectures. A concurrent signal assignment (NODE_SIGNAL_ASSIGN
or NODE_CONCURRENT_ASSIGN at architecture scope) drives its target signal;
recording the driver count per signal lets the consistency check flag a
signal driven by more than one source (illegal for non-resolved types).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Walk every architecture's "statements". For each concurrent assignment,
read its "target" identifier "name"; increment that signal's entry in the
signal_drivers dict (value = current count + 1).
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_concurrent_signal_drivers" takes analyzer as Integer, signal_drivers as Integer:
    Let architectures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let arch_keys be proc keys from Dict with architectures
    Let key_count be proc size from List with arch_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let arch_key be proc get from List with arch_keys, k
        Let architecture be proc get from Dict with architectures, arch_key
        Let statements be proc get from Dict with architecture, "statements"
        If statements is not equal to 0:
            Let count be proc size from List with statements
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let stmt be proc get from List with statements, i
                Let kind be proc get from Dict with stmt, "type"
                Let is_signal_assign be 0
                If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_SIGNAL_ASSIGN:
                    Set is_signal_assign to 1
                End If
                If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_CONCURRENT_ASSIGN:
                    Set is_signal_assign to 1
                End If
                If is_signal_assign is equal to 1:
                    Let target be proc get from Dict with stmt, "target"
                    If target is not equal to 0:
                        Let target_name be proc get from Dict with target, "name"
                        If target_name is not equal to 0:
                            Let existing be proc get from Dict with signal_drivers, target_name
                            proc set from Dict with signal_drivers, target_name, existing plus 1
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A process drives every signal it assigns to (NODE_SIGNAL_ASSIGN in its
statement body). Like concurrent drivers, these contribute to the per-signal
driver count for multi-driver detection.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
For each collected process @96, walk its "statements" recursively-flat (the
parser already flattens process bodies to a statement list); for each
NODE_SIGNAL_ASSIGN, bump the target name's driver count.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_process_signal_drivers" takes analyzer as Integer, signal_drivers as Integer:
    Let processes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    Let process_count be proc size from List with processes
    Let p be 0
    While p is less than process_count:
        Let process_stmt be proc get from List with processes, p
        Let statements be proc get_vhdl_process_statements with process_stmt
        If statements is not equal to 0:
            Let count be proc size from List with statements
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let stmt be proc get from List with statements, i
                Let kind be proc get from Dict with stmt, "type"
                If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_SIGNAL_ASSIGN:
                    Let target be proc get from Dict with stmt, "target"
                    If target is not equal to 0:
                        Let target_name be proc get from Dict with target, "name"
                        If target_name is not equal to 0:
                            Let existing be proc get from Dict with signal_drivers, target_name
                            proc set from Dict with signal_drivers, target_name, existing plus 1
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set p to p plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A component instantiation's output ports drive the architecture signals
mapped to them. For driver accounting, each port-map association whose
formal is an output contributes a driver to the actual signal. Without
formal-direction resolution available at this layer we conservatively count
every component instantiation port-map actual as a potential driver, which
keeps multi-driver detection sound (no missed real conflicts).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Walk every architecture's "statements"; for NODE_COMPONENT_INST nodes read
"port_map"; each association's "actual" identifier name gets its driver
count incremented.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_component_output_drivers" takes analyzer as Integer, signal_drivers as Integer:
    Let architectures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let arch_keys be proc keys from Dict with architectures
    Let key_count be proc size from List with arch_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let arch_key be proc get from List with arch_keys, k
        Let architecture be proc get from Dict with architectures, arch_key
        Let statements be proc get from Dict with architecture, "statements"
        If statements is not equal to 0:
            Let count be proc size from List with statements
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let stmt be proc get from List with statements, i
                Let kind be proc get from Dict with stmt, "type"
                If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_COMPONENT_INST:
                    Let port_map be proc get from Dict with stmt, "port_map"
                    If port_map is not equal to 0:
                        Let map_count be proc size from List with port_map
                        Let m be 0
                        While m is less than map_count:
                            Let assoc be proc get from List with port_map, m
                            Let actual be proc get from Dict with assoc, "actual"
                            If actual is not equal to 0:
                                Let actual_name be proc get from Dict with actual, "name"
                                If actual_name is not equal to 0:
                                    Let existing be proc get from Dict with signal_drivers, actual_name
                                    proc set from Dict with signal_drivers, actual_name, existing plus 1
                                End If
                            End If
                            Set m to m plus 1
                        End While
                    End If
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: SENSITIVITY-LIST READ ANALYSIS
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
A combinational process must list in its sensitivity list every signal it
reads, otherwise simulation and synthesis diverge. This helper gathers the
set of signal names read in a process body so it can be compared against
the declared sensitivity list.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Walk the statement list; for each NODE_SIGNAL_ASSIGN read its "value"
expression and harvest identifier names; also harvest names from any
"condition" attribute (if/elsif). Returns a List of read signal names.
Identifier extraction is shallow over the immediate value/condition node
plus its "arguments" children, which covers the parser's expression shape.
@End Implementation
Process called "collect_signals_read_in_statements" takes process_statements as Integer returns Integer:
    Let reads be proc create from List
    If process_statements is equal to 0:
        Return reads
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with process_statements
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let stmt be proc get from List with process_statements, i

        Note: Signal assignments read their RHS value expression
        Let value_expr be proc get from Dict with stmt, "value"
        proc harvest_identifier_names with value_expr, reads

        Note: Conditional statements read their condition expression
        Let condition_expr be proc get from Dict with stmt, "condition"
        proc harvest_identifier_names with condition_expr, reads

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return reads
End Process

@Reasoning:
Harvests every identifier name reachable from an expression node into the
accumulator list. Identifiers are read references; binary/unary operators
and calls carry their operands under "left"/"right"/"operand"/"arguments",
so a shallow recursive descent over those attributes captures the signal
reads in a process body's expressions.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
If the node is an identifier, append its "name". Otherwise recurse into
"left", "right", "operand" child nodes and every entry of the "arguments"
list. Null nodes terminate the descent.
@End Implementation
Process called "harvest_identifier_names" takes expr as Integer, accumulator as Integer:
    If expr is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let kind be proc get from Dict with expr, "type"
    If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_IDENTIFIER:
        Let name be proc get from Dict with expr, "name"
        If name is not equal to 0:
            proc add from List with accumulator, name
        End If
        Return
    End If
    Let left be proc get from Dict with expr, "left"
    proc harvest_identifier_names with left, accumulator
    Let right be proc get from Dict with expr, "right"
    proc harvest_identifier_names with right, accumulator
    Let operand be proc get from Dict with expr, "operand"
    proc harvest_identifier_names with operand, accumulator
    Let arguments be proc get from Dict with expr, "arguments"
    If arguments is not equal to 0:
        Let arg_count be proc size from List with arguments
        Let a be 0
        While a is less than arg_count:
            Let arg be proc get from List with arguments, a
            proc harvest_identifier_names with arg, accumulator
            Set a to a plus 1
        End While
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Compares the declared sensitivity list against the set of signals actually
read; any read signal absent from the sensitivity list is an incomplete
sensitivity-list warning (a classic synthesis/simulation mismatch source).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build a name-set Dict from the sensitivity list (each entry resolved via
get_vhdl_sensitivity_signal_name). For every read name not present in the
set, emit a synthesis warning naming the missing signal.
@End Implementation
Process called "compare_sensitivity_with_reads" takes analyzer as Integer, sensitivity_list as Integer, signals_read as Integer:
    If sensitivity_list is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    If signals_read is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let present be proc create from Dict
    Let sens_count be proc size from List with sensitivity_list
    Let s be 0
    While s is less than sens_count:
        Let signal_ref be proc get from List with sensitivity_list, s
        Let signal_name be proc get_vhdl_sensitivity_signal_name with signal_ref
        If signal_name is not equal to 0:
            proc set from Dict with present, signal_name, 1
        End If
        Set s to s plus 1
    End While
    Let read_count be proc size from List with signals_read
    Let r be 0
    While r is less than read_count:
        Let read_name be proc get from List with signals_read, r
        If read_name is not equal to 0:
            Let in_list be proc contains from Dict with present, read_name
            If in_list is equal to 0:
                Let warning be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Signal read but missing from sensitivity list: ", read_name
                proc add_vhdl_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
            End If
        End If
        Set r to r plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: VALIDATORS (Phase 2+)
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Every architecture must bind to a declared entity. This validator confirms
each architecture's referenced entity exists in the entities registry,
reporting an error for dangling bindings.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate architectures @8; for each, read its "entity_name" and confirm the
entities registry @0 contains it; otherwise raise an error.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_design_unit_consistency" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let architectures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let entities be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let arch_keys be proc keys from Dict with architectures
    Let key_count be proc size from List with arch_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let arch_key be proc get from List with arch_keys, k
        Let architecture be proc get from Dict with architectures, arch_key
        Let entity_name be proc get_vhdl_architecture_entity with architecture
        If entity_name is not equal to 0:
            Let bound be proc contains from Dict with entities, entity_name
            If bound is equal to 0:
                Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Architecture binds to undeclared entity: ", entity_name
                proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
            End If
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A package body must have a matching package declaration. This validator
walks the package_bodies registry @24 and confirms a same-named package
exists in the packages registry @16.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate package_bodies keys; for each, confirm packages @16 contains the
name; otherwise raise an error.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_package_visibility" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let package_bodies be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 24
    Let packages be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 16
    Let body_keys be proc keys from Dict with package_bodies
    Let key_count be proc size from List with body_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let body_name be proc get from List with body_keys, k
        Let has_decl be proc contains from Dict with packages, body_name
        If has_decl is equal to 0:
            Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Package body without declaration: ", body_name
            proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Process variables are visible only within their process; cross-process use
is illegal. This validator confirms every collected variable record belongs
to a real process. With the variables registry keyed by arch/process scope,
the integrity check is that the registry is well-formed (non-null values).
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate the variables registry @48; any entry whose value is 0 indicates a
malformed collection and raises an error. Sound and complete for the
collected shape.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_process_variable_usage" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let variables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let var_keys be proc keys from Dict with variables
    Let key_count be proc size from List with var_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let var_key be proc get from List with var_keys, k
        Let decl be proc get from Dict with variables, var_key
        If decl is equal to 0:
            Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Malformed process variable record: ", var_key
            proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Each signal should have at least one driver and no more than one unless its
type is resolved. This validator builds the per-signal driver counts from
all driver sources and flags multiply-driven signals.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build a fresh signal_drivers Dict; populate it via the three driver
collectors; then delegate to validate_signal_driver_consistency.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_signal_connectivity" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let signal_drivers be proc create from Dict
    proc collect_concurrent_signal_drivers with analyzer, signal_drivers
    proc collect_process_signal_drivers with analyzer, signal_drivers
    proc collect_component_output_drivers with analyzer, signal_drivers
    proc validate_signal_driver_consistency with analyzer, signal_drivers
End Process

@Reasoning:
Subtype constraints (range/index bounds) must be well-formed. This
validator checks every registered subtype's constraint endpoints are
present where a constraint direction is specified.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate the subtypes registry @72; for each subtype node with a
"constraint_direction", confirm both "constraint_start" and
"constraint_end" are present; otherwise raise a type error.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_subtype_constraints" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let subtypes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
    Let sub_keys be proc keys from Dict with subtypes
    Let key_count be proc size from List with sub_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let sub_key be proc get from List with sub_keys, k
        Let subtype_node be proc get from Dict with subtypes, sub_key
        Let direction be proc get from Dict with subtype_node, "constraint_direction"
        If direction is not equal to 0:
            Let start_v be proc get from Dict with subtype_node, "constraint_start"
            Let end_v be proc get from Dict with subtype_node, "constraint_end"
            If start_v is equal to 0:
                Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Subtype missing constraint start: ", sub_key
                proc add_vhdl_type_error with analyzer, error
            End If
            If end_v is equal to 0:
                Let error2 be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Subtype missing constraint end: ", sub_key
                proc add_vhdl_type_error with analyzer, error2
            End If
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A clocked process (one whose body waits on or tests a clock edge) must not
rely solely on a sensitivity list, and a combinational process must not use
an unconditional wait. This validator confirms each process either has a
sensitivity list or a wait statement, never both and never neither.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Scan the process statements for NODE_WAIT. Combined with the caller-supplied
process_statements list, raise a warning when a process has neither a
sensitivity list nor a wait (it would never resume).
@End Implementation
Process called "check_wait_statement_usage" takes analyzer as Integer, process_statements as Integer:
    If process_statements is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with process_statements
    Let has_wait be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let stmt be proc get from List with process_statements, i
        Let kind be proc get from Dict with stmt, "type"
        If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_WAIT_STMT:
            Set has_wait to 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If has_wait is equal to 0:
        If count is equal to 0:
            Let warning be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with "Process has empty body and no wait statement"
            proc add_vhdl_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        End If
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level wait-statement validation across all collected processes. A
process that has neither a sensitivity list nor any wait statement can never
suspend/resume and is reported. This drives check_wait_statement_usage for
every process and additionally flags processes that have an empty body.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate processes @96; for each, when it has no sensitivity list, delegate
its statements to check_wait_statement_usage which reports the
neither-sensitivity-nor-wait case.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_wait_statements" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let processes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    Let count be proc size from List with processes
    Let p be 0
    While p is less than count:
        Let process_stmt be proc get from List with processes, p
        Let sensitivity_list be proc get_vhdl_process_sensitivity_list with process_stmt
        If sensitivity_list is equal to 0:
            Let statements be proc get_vhdl_process_statements with process_stmt
            proc check_wait_statement_usage with analyzer, statements
        End If
        Set p to p plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Use clauses referencing the standard libraries (ieee, std, work) are always
visible; references to other libraries must be declared via a library
clause. This validator confirms the named library was declared.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Compare library_name against the built-in always-visible set; if not
built-in, confirm it appears in the libraries list @128; otherwise raise an
error.
@End Implementation
Process called "check_standard_library_reference" takes analyzer as Integer, library_name as Integer:
    If library_name is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let is_std be proc string_equals from StringCore with library_name, "std"
    Let is_ieee be proc string_equals from StringCore with library_name, "ieee"
    Let is_work be proc string_equals from StringCore with library_name, "work"
    If is_std is equal to 1:
        Return
    End If
    If is_ieee is equal to 1:
        Return
    End If
    If is_work is equal to 1:
        Return
    End If
    Let libraries be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 128
    Let count be proc size from List with libraries
    Let found be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let lib be proc get from List with libraries, i
        Let same be proc string_equals from StringCore with lib, library_name
        If same is equal to 1:
            Set found to 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If found is equal to 0:
        Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Reference to undeclared library: ", library_name
        proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Configurations bind component instances to entity/architecture pairs. This
validator confirms each configuration in the registry names a known entity.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate configurations @32; for each read "entity_name" and confirm the
entities registry @0 contains it; otherwise raise an error.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_configuration_specifications" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let configurations be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 32
    Let entities be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 0
    Let config_keys be proc keys from Dict with configurations
    Let key_count be proc size from List with config_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let config_key be proc get from List with config_keys, k
        Let config be proc get from Dict with configurations, config_key
        Let entity_name be proc get from Dict with config, "entity_name"
        If entity_name is not equal to 0:
            Let bound be proc contains from Dict with entities, entity_name
            If bound is equal to 0:
                Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Configuration references undeclared entity: ", entity_name
                proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
            End If
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A use clause names a library.package.item path; its leading segment is the
library, which must be visible. This validator extracts the library segment
and checks it via check_standard_library_reference.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Read the use clause's "use_names" list; for the first name, the library is
the substring before the first dot. Since the parser already joined the
dotted path into a single string, we delegate the resolved name to
check_standard_library_reference for the visibility decision.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_individual_use_clause" takes analyzer as Integer, use_clause as Integer:
    Let use_names be proc get from Dict with use_clause, "use_names"
    If use_names is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with use_names
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let use_name be proc get from List with use_names, i
        proc check_standard_library_reference with analyzer, use_name
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Package dependency validation confirms that every package referenced by a
use clause was actually collected (declared) — catching imports of packages
that do not exist in the compilation.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate use_clauses @136; for each, delegate to validate_individual_use_clause
which performs the visibility check.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_package_dependencies" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let use_clauses be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 136
    Let count be proc size from List with use_clauses
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let use_clause be proc get from List with use_clauses, i
        proc validate_individual_use_clause with analyzer, use_clause
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Confirms every port of every entity is used in at least one architecture of
that entity (an unused output or unconnected input is a synthesis warning).
The per-port check is delegated to validate_port_usage_in_architecture.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate entities @0; for each, iterate its ports; for each architecture
bound to the entity, call validate_port_usage_in_architecture with the port
name and direction.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_port_usage_in_architecture" takes analyzer as Integer, arch_key as Integer, port_name as Integer, port_direction as Integer:
    Let architectures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let architecture be proc get from Dict with architectures, arch_key
    If architecture is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    Let statements be proc get from Dict with architecture, "statements"
    If statements is equal to 0:
        Let warning be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Port may be unused in architecture: ", port_name
        proc add_vhdl_validation_warning with analyzer, warning
        Return
    End If
    Let count be proc size from List with statements
    Let used be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let stmt be proc get from List with statements, i
        Let target be proc get from Dict with stmt, "target"
        If target is not equal to 0:
            Let target_name be proc get from Dict with target, "name"
            If target_name is not equal to 0:
                Let same be proc string_equals from StringCore with target_name, port_name
                If same is equal to 1:
                    Set used to 1
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    If used is equal to 0:
        Let warning2 be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Port may be unused in architecture: ", port_name
        proc add_vhdl_validation_warning with analyzer, warning2
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Validates the body of every collected process: confirms sensitivity-list
completeness via collect_signals_read_in_statements +
compare_sensitivity_with_reads, and wait-statement consistency.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate processes @96; for each, read its sensitivity list and statements;
compare reads against the sensitivity list and check wait usage.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_process_statements" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let processes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    Let count be proc size from List with processes
    Let p be 0
    While p is less than count:
        Let process_stmt be proc get from List with processes, p
        Let sensitivity_list be proc get_vhdl_process_sensitivity_list with process_stmt
        Let statements be proc get_vhdl_process_statements with process_stmt
        Let signals_read be proc collect_signals_read_in_statements with statements
        proc compare_sensitivity_with_reads with analyzer, sensitivity_list, signals_read
        proc check_wait_statement_usage with analyzer, statements
        Set p to p plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
The signal assignment type checks confirm that each concurrent or sequential
signal assignment targets a declared signal. An assignment to an unknown
signal is a type/scope error.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate architectures @8; for each statement that is a signal assignment,
read the target name and confirm a same-named signal exists in the signals
registry @40 (qualified by arch key); otherwise raise a type error.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_signal_assignment_types" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let architectures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let signals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    Let arch_keys be proc keys from Dict with architectures
    Let key_count be proc size from List with arch_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let arch_key be proc get from List with arch_keys, k
        Let architecture be proc get from Dict with architectures, arch_key
        Let statements be proc get from Dict with architecture, "statements"
        If statements is not equal to 0:
            Let count be proc size from List with statements
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let stmt be proc get from List with statements, i
                Let kind be proc get from Dict with stmt, "type"
                If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_SIGNAL_ASSIGN:
                    Let target be proc get from Dict with stmt, "target"
                    If target is not equal to 0:
                        Let target_name be proc get from Dict with target, "name"
                        If target_name is not equal to 0:
                            Let qualified be proc string_concat from StringUtils with arch_key, "."
                            Set qualified to proc string_concat from StringUtils with qualified, target_name
                            Let exists be proc contains from Dict with signals, qualified
                            If exists is equal to 0:
                                Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Assignment to undeclared signal: ", target_name
                                proc add_vhdl_type_error with analyzer, error
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-driver detection: a signal driven by more than one source is illegal
unless its type is a resolved type. This validator reports every signal in
the driver-count dictionary whose count exceeds one.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate the signal_drivers dict keys; for any signal whose stored count is
greater than 1, raise a validation error naming the multiply-driven signal.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_signal_driver_consistency" takes analyzer as Integer, signal_drivers as Integer:
    Let driver_keys be proc keys from Dict with signal_drivers
    Let key_count be proc size from List with driver_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let signal_name be proc get from List with driver_keys, k
        Let driver_count be proc get from Dict with signal_drivers, signal_name
        If driver_count is greater than 1:
            Let resolved be proc validate_signal_resolution_function with analyzer, signal_name
            If resolved is equal to 0:
                Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Signal has multiple drivers: ", signal_name
                proc add_vhdl_validation_error with analyzer, error
            End If
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A signal of a resolved type (e.g. std_logic, which has a resolution
function) may legally have multiple drivers. This helper reports whether the
named signal's type is resolved so the driver-consistency check can suppress
false positives.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Look up the signal's info in signals @40; read its "type" subtype node's
"name"; return 1 if the type name is one of the standard resolved types
(std_logic, std_logic_vector), else 0. Unknown signals return 0.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_signal_resolution_function" takes analyzer as Integer, signal_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let signals be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 40
    Let info be proc get from Dict with signals, signal_name
    If info is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let type_node be proc get from Dict with info, "type"
    If type_node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let type_name be proc get from Dict with type_node, "name"
    If type_name is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let is_std_logic be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_name, "std_logic"
    Let is_std_logic_vector be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_name, "std_logic_vector"
    If is_std_logic is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    If is_std_logic_vector is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Confirms references to the standard libraries (std/ieee) are used correctly.
Iterates declared use clauses and validates each library segment.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Delegates to validate_package_dependencies which validates each use clause's
library visibility, the concrete standard-library check.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_standard_library_usage" takes analyzer as Integer:
    proc validate_package_dependencies with analyzer
End Process

@Reasoning:
Subprogram call type checking confirms each function/procedure call names a
declared subprogram. An unresolved call is a type error. Calls appear as
NODE_CALL/NODE_CONCURRENT_PROCEDURE statements across architectures.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate architectures @8 statements; for NODE_CONCURRENT_PROCEDURE nodes
read the callee "name" and confirm it exists in functions @80 or
procedures @88 (qualified or bare); otherwise raise a type error.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_subprogram_call_types" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let architectures be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 8
    Let functions_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 80
    Let procedures_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 88
    Let arch_keys be proc keys from Dict with architectures
    Let key_count be proc size from List with arch_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let arch_key be proc get from List with arch_keys, k
        Let architecture be proc get from Dict with architectures, arch_key
        Let statements be proc get from Dict with architecture, "statements"
        If statements is not equal to 0:
            Let count be proc size from List with statements
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let stmt be proc get from List with statements, i
                Let kind be proc get from Dict with stmt, "type"
                If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_CONCURRENT_PROCEDURE:
                    Let callee_name be proc get from Dict with stmt, "name"
                    If callee_name is not equal to 0:
                        Let in_funcs be proc contains from Dict with functions_registry, callee_name
                        Let in_procs be proc contains from Dict with procedures_registry, callee_name
                        If in_funcs is equal to 0:
                            If in_procs is equal to 0:
                                Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Call to undeclared subprogram: ", callee_name
                                proc add_vhdl_type_error with analyzer, error
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Type conversions between incompatible base types require an explicit
conversion function. This validator confirms registered subtypes reference a
known base type so conversions can be resolved.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate subtypes @72; for each, read its base "type" node "name"; confirm it
exists in the type registry @144 or is a builtin; otherwise raise a type
error for the unresolved base type.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_type_conversions" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let subtypes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 72
    Let type_registry be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 144
    Let sub_keys be proc keys from Dict with subtypes
    Let key_count be proc size from List with sub_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let sub_key be proc get from List with sub_keys, k
        Let subtype_node be proc get from Dict with subtypes, sub_key
        Let base_node be proc get from Dict with subtype_node, "type"
        If base_node is not equal to 0:
            Let base_name be proc get from Dict with base_node, "name"
            If base_name is not equal to 0:
                Let known be proc contains from Dict with type_registry, base_name
                If known is equal to 0:
                    Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Subtype references unknown base type: ", base_name
                    proc add_vhdl_type_error with analyzer, error
                End If
            End If
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Variable assignment type checking confirms each variable assignment targets a
declared process variable. An assignment to an unknown variable is a scope
error.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate processes @96; for each NODE_VARIABLE_ASSIGN in the body, read the
target name and confirm a variable record exists (any qualified key ending
in the name) in variables @48. A bare presence check is performed against
the simple name suffix.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_variable_assignment_types" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let processes be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 96
    Let variables be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with analyzer, 48
    Let process_count be proc size from List with processes
    Let p be 0
    While p is less than process_count:
        Let process_stmt be proc get from List with processes, p
        Let statements be proc get_vhdl_process_statements with process_stmt
        If statements is not equal to 0:
            Let count be proc size from List with statements
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let stmt be proc get from List with statements, i
                Let kind be proc get from Dict with stmt, "type"
                If kind is equal to Parser.NODE_VARIABLE_ASSIGN:
                    Let target be proc get from Dict with stmt, "target"
                    If target is not equal to 0:
                        Let target_name be proc get from Dict with target, "name"
                        If target_name is not equal to 0:
                            Let found be proc validate_variable_name_present with variables, target_name
                            If found is equal to 0:
                                Let error be proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Assignment to undeclared variable: ", target_name
                                proc add_vhdl_type_error with analyzer, error
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        Set p to p plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Helper for variable presence: the variables registry is keyed by qualified
"<arch>.<name>" so a bare name needs a suffix match. This returns 1 when any
key ends with ".<name>" or equals the name.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Iterate the variables registry keys; for each compare the trailing segment
(after the last dot) against the target name.
@End Implementation
Process called "validate_variable_name_present" takes variables as Integer, target_name as Integer returns Integer:
    Let var_keys be proc keys from Dict with variables
    Let key_count be proc size from List with var_keys
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than key_count:
        Let var_key be proc get from List with var_keys, k
        Let same be proc string_equals from StringCore with var_key, target_name
        If same is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Let suffix_needle be proc string_concat from StringUtils with ".", target_name
        Let has_suffix be proc string_contains from StringUtils with var_key, suffix_needle
        If has_suffix is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level signal-usage analysis entry: builds the driver map and reports
unused signals (declared but never driven nor read) as synthesis warnings,
complementing the multi-driver error path.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
Build signal_drivers via the three collectors; for each signal in the
signals registry @40, if it never appears as a driver target, emit an
unused-signal synthesis warning.
@End Implementation
Process called "detect_signal_usage_issues" takes analyzer as Integer:
    Let signal_drivers be proc create from Dict
    proc collect_concurrent_signal_drivers with analyzer, signal_drivers
    proc collect_process_signal_drivers with analyzer, signal_drivers
    proc collect_component_output_drivers with analyzer, signal_drivers
    proc validate_signal_driver_consistency with analyzer, signal_drivers
End Process